data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core+. It's completely removed.
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws.** The entire `ThreadAbortException` pattern is dead.
3. **`ThreadAbortException` is never raised** by the runtime — your `catch` block is dead code.

The modern replacement is **`CancellationToken`** with cooperative cancellation.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        // Task.Run uses the thread pool — no manual Thread needed
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — roll back partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit loop cleanly; finally still runs
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        // Signal cooperative cancellation
        _cts.Cancel();

        // Wait with a timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
        var effectiveTimeout = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(effectiveTimeout)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Worker didn't stop in time — log it, but you CANNOT force-kill it.
            // This is by design in .NET 8.
            Log.Warning("Worker did not stop within timeout");
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Blocking calls ignore cancellation** | If `GetNextItem()` blocks on a `Monitor.Wait` or unmanaged call, `CancellationToken` won't interrupt it. You must redesign the blocking call to accept a token (e.g., use `BlockingCollection<T>.Take(token)` or `SemaphoreSlim.WaitAsync(token)`). |
| **No forced termination** | .NET 8 has **no equivalent** to `Thread.Abort()`. If code hangs in unmanaged/CPU-bound work that doesn't check the token, it will hang forever. Design all work to be cooperatively cancellable. |
| **`catch (ThreadAbortException)` silently becomes dead code** | It compiles but never catches anything. A subtle bug if you rely on it for rollback — the rollback just stops happening with no error. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort()` throws at runtime** | If you miss removing it, your code compiles fine but throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime. |
| **`volatile bool` is insufficient** | A `volatile bool` can't wake a blocked thread. `CancellationToken` can — it supports `WaitHandle` registration and `OperationCanceledException` propagation. |
| **Dispose the CancellationTokenSource** | `CTS` registers callbacks internally. Leaking it leaks memory. |

### If You Truly Need Forced Termination

The only remaining option is **`Environment.FailFast()`** (kills the process) or isolating work in a **separate process** you can kill. In-process forced thread termination is gone for good — it was always unsafe (corrupted locks, leaked resources, torn state).
